item.title: 'Squid Game' Is the Dystopian Netflix Hit No One Wanted---Until Everyone Did
item.description: The South Korean phenomenon might become Netflix’s biggest hit ever, but for a decade, local studios rejected the show’s pitch as too grotesque and too unrealistic.

item.title: Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte Announces Retirement from Politics
item.description: Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte, whose brash and authoritarian style has upended governance in the country, said that he intends to retire from politics, indicating he won’t seek the vice presidency next year.

item.title: Countdown Starts on Chinese Company Delistings After U.S.-China Audit Fight
item.description: U.S. regulators gear up for a three-year countdown that will force many Chinese companies to leave American stock exchanges, after a long impasse between Washington and Beijing over access to the companies’ audit records.

item.title: Blinken Heading to Paris on a Fence-Mending Mission
item.description: Secretary of State will meet French counterparts as administration works to heal a rift after its Australian submarine deal.

item.title: Fashion Mogul Agrees to Extradition to U.S. to Face Sex Charges
item.description: Peter Nygard, the Canadian fashion and retailing executive, faces charges of sex trafficking and racketeering and has been accused of criminal conduct involving dozens of victims in the U.S., Canada and the Bahamas.

item.title: China's Power Shortfalls Begin to Ripple Around the World
item.description: Widespread power shortfalls have hurt the recovery of the world’s second-largest economy and add to a global energy squeeze that risks upsetting the post-pandemic recovery.

item.title: U.S. Poised to Unveil China Trade Policy
item.description: The Biden administration will begin to share its China strategy with a speech on Monday by U.S. Trade Representative Katherine Tai, as business groups press the administration for clarity.

item.title: Russia Seeks to Protect Economy From Energy Transition
item.description: The country is looking to limit spending from its sovereign-wealth fund as the global transition away from fossil fuels threatens the backbone of its economy.

item.title: U.N. Warns of Humanitarian Crisis in Ethiopia's Tigray Region
item.description: The organization said only a fraction of needed aid is being allowed into Tigray, which has been at war with the government in Addis Ababa for almost a year.
